{"cursor":"2788","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\nThe 'ConvenciÃ³n Nacional Bautista de MÃ©xico' ('National Baptist Convention of\nMexico') is the oldest and largest Baptist group in Mexico. The first\nevangelical church in Mexico was a Baptist church organized on January 30, 1864\nin Monterrey, Nuevo LeÃ³n. James Hickey, a Baptist and a member of the American\nBible Society, constituted this church with himself and four other members -\nThomas Westrup, JosÃ© Maria Uranga, Arcadio Uranga, and Mrs. Hickey. By 1869,\nWestrup and the Uranga brothers had organized six more churches. The American\nBaptist Home Mission Society and the Southern Baptist Convention sent about\nfifty missionaries to Mexico before the beginning of the 20th century. In 1884,\nthe Coahuila Baptist Association was organized in Saltillo, and in 1885 the\nNuevo LeÃ³n Baptist Association was organized in Monterrey. After the turn of the\ncentury, Alejandro TreviÃ±o, John Cheavens and James Chastain proposed the idea\nof organizing a national convention. Forty-three church messengers met at the\nPrimera Iglesia Bautista (First Baptist Church) in Mexico City in September\n1903. From this gathering came a provisional constitution for the National\nConvention, and the groundwork for missionary, theological and publications\nministries. This began a transition of the work from leadership by foreign\nmissionaries to leadership by national pastors. In 1904, the National Convention\nselected Alejandro TreviÃ±o to represent them at the first Baptist World\nCongress, from which was formed the Baptist World Alliance.\n\nThe National Convention currently is engaged in missionary, theological,\npublication, and benevolent work, as well as carrying on work among the students\nin 3 large universities. It operates the Mexican Baptist Theological Seminary in\nMexico City and the Dr. G. H. Lacy Seminary in Oaxaca, Oaxaca, and owns six\nbookstores. La Luz Bautista (The Baptist Light) is the official periodical of\nthe Convention. In 1991, there were 35 associations with 888 churches and 66,398\nmembers in cooperation with the National Baptist Convention of Mexico. In 1993,\nthe Convention was able to gain official recognition through registration with\nthe Office of Religious Affairs.\n","linknr":132,"url":"National_Baptist_Convention_of_Mexico","recorded":1375059304,"links":["/w/index.php?title=National_Baptist_Convention_of_Mexico&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=National_Baptist_Convention_of_Mexico&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls.nojs%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","//meta.wikimedia.org","#mw-navigation","#p-search","/wiki/Category:Baptist","/wiki/Baptists","/wiki/File:Baptism_logo.jpg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/3/3a/Baptism_logo.jpg/100px-Baptism_logo.jpg","/wiki/Christianity","/wiki/Protestantism","/wiki/Puritan","/wiki/Anabaptist","/wiki/Baptist_beliefs","/wiki/Priesthood_of_all_believers","/wiki/Soul_competency","/wiki/Baptists_in_the_history_of_separation_of_church_and_state","/wiki/Sola_scriptura","/wiki/Congregationalist_polity","/wiki/Baptist_ordinance","/wiki/Baptist_offices","/wiki/List_of_Baptist_confessions","/wiki/List_of_Baptists","/wiki/John_Smyth_(Baptist_minister)","/wiki/Thomas_Helwys","/wiki/Roger_Williams_(theologian)","/wiki/John_Cl